utheast Asia in world history'' (Oxford UP, 2009).\n* Ropp, Paul S. ''China in World History'' (Oxford UP, 2010)\n\n===Economic history===\n* Allen, G.C. ''A Short Economic History Of Modern Japan 1867-1937'' (1945) [https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.263052/page/n3 online]; also [https://archive.org/details/shorteconomichis00alle  1981 edition free to borrow]\n* Cowan, C.D. ed.  ''The economic development of China and Japan: studies in economic history and political economy'' (1964) [https://archive.org/details/economicdevelopm0000cowa online free to borrow]\n* Jones, Eric. ''The European miracle: environments, economies and geopolitics in the history of Europe and Asia. (Cambridge UP, 2003).\n*  Lockwood, William W. ''The economic development of Japan; growth and structural change'' (1970) [https://archive.org/details/economicdevelopm00lock online free to borrow]\n* Pomeranz, Kenneth. ''The Great Divergence: China, Europe, and the Making of the Modern World Economy.'' (2001)\n* Schulz-Forberg, Hagen, ed. ''A Global Conceptual History of Asia, 1860\u20131940'' (2015)\n* Smith, Alan K. ''Creating a World Economy: Merchant Capital, Colonialism, and World Trade, 1400-1825'' (Routledge, 2019).\n* Von Glahn, Richard. ''The Economic History of China'' (2016)\n\n{{Asia topics}}\n{{History of Asia}}\n{{History by continent}}\n\n[[Category:History of Asia| ]]\n", "name_user": "Ruenard", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_Asia"}
{"title_page": "Titus Bramble", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Titus Bramble\n| image = Titus Bramble 2011.jpg\n| image_size = 250\n| alt = \n| caption = Bramble playing for [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] in 2011\n| fullname = Titus Malachi Bramble<ref name=\"Statistics\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.premierleague.com/staticFiles/7b/53/0,,12306~152443,00.pdf |title=Statistics |publisher=Premier League |format=PDF |access-date=3 August 2010}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=y|1981|7|31}}\n| birth_place = [[Ipswich]], England\n| height = {{height|m=1.85}}<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/players/1890/Titus-Bramble/overview |title=Premier League Player Profile |publisher=Premier League |access-date=24 March 2011}}</ref>\n| position = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| currentclub = [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] (academy coach)\n| youthyears1 = 1996\u20131998\n| youthclubs1 = [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]]\n| years1 = 1998\u20132002\n| clubs1 = [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]]\n| caps1 = 48\n| goals1 = 1\n| years2 = 1999\u20132000\n| clubs2 = \u2192 [[Colchester United F.C.|Colchester United]] (loan)\n| caps2 = 2\n| goals2 = 0\n| years3 = 2002\u20132007\n| clubs3 = [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]]\n| caps3 = 105\n| goals3 = 3\n| years4 = 2007\u20132010\n| clubs4 = [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]]\n| caps4 = 96\n| goals4 = 5\n| years5 = 2010\u20132013\n| clubs5 = [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]]\n| caps5 = 47\n| goals5 = 1\n| years6 = 2017\n| clubs6 = [[Stowmarket Town F.C.|Stowmarket Town]]\n| caps6 = 1\n| goals6 = 0\n| nationalyears1 = 2000\u20132002\n| nationalteam1 = [[England national under-21 football team|England U21]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 10\n| nationalgoals1 = 1\n}}\n'''Titus Malachi  Bramble''' (born 31 July 1981) is an English [[association football|footballer]] who plays for [[Stowmarket Town F.C.|Stowmarket Town]]. He is also an academy coach at [[Ipswich Town]].<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{Cite news |last=Law |first=James |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40898339 |title=Titus Bramble: Ex-Newcastle United & Sunderland defender joins Stowmarket Town |date=11 August 2017 |work=BBC Sport |access-date=29 April 2019}}</ref> He played as a [[centre-back]] and is widely regarded as one of the best players of his generation.\n  \nBramble played in the [[Premier League]] over thirteen consecutive seasons from 2000 and 2013, representing [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]], [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]], [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]] and [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]]. After being released by Sunderland in 2013, he spent several years in a coaching capacity at Ipswich, with whom he began his career in 1998.\n\nAt international level, he made 10 appearances for the [[England national under-21 football team|England under-21s]] from 2000 and 2002.\n\n==Playing career==\n\n===Ipswich Town===\nBorn in [[Ipswich]], Suffolk, Bramble started his career at home town club [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]]. After making his debut in the 1998\u201399 season,<ref name=\"Soccerbase9899\" /> Bramble went on to make 48 league appearances for the club, spending a brief period on loan at [[Colchester United F.C.|Colchester United]] over the [[1999\u20132000 Football League|1999\u20132000 season]].<ref name=\"sb\" /> He scored four goals for Ipswich,<ref name=\"sb\" /> with strikes against [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] in the league,<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/l/leeds_united/897188.stm |title=Ipswich see off Sunderland |date=26 August 2000 |access-date=27 February 2010 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]] and Coventry in the League Cup and [[Torpedo Moscow]] in the [[UEFA Cup]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/worthington_cup/941716.stm |title=Ipswich 5\u20130 Millwall (Agg: 5\u20132) |date=26 September 2000 |access-date=27 February 2010 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/worthington_cup/1043830.stm |title=Ipswich see off Sky Blues again |date=28 November 2000 |access-date=27 February 2010 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/uefa_cup/1553044.stm |title=Bramble maintains Ipswich record |date=20 September 2001 |access-date=27 February 2010 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\n===Newcastle United===\nBramble joined Newcastle in July 2002 for \u00a36&nbsp;million, vowing at the time to make himself indispensable to then manager [[Bobby Robson|Sir Bobby Robson]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/n/newcastle_united/2094361.stm |title=BBC SPORT &#124; Football &#124; Teams &#124; Newcastle United &#124; Bramble bids for starring role |date=4 July 2002 |access-date=21 March 2009 |publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the 2003\u201304 season, readers of the football e-mail newsletter [[The Fiver]] voted Bramble as the worst player of the year in the [[Premier League]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Smyth |first=Rob |url=http://football.guardian.co.uk/Fiver/0,,1222154,00.html |title=Underdogs, and Prized horses &#124; News &#124; Guardian Unlimited Football |date=21 May 2004 |access-date=21 March 2009 |publisher=Football.guardian.co.uk |location=London}}</ref> Bramble scored a volleyed goal against league champions [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] on 8 May 2006 in a 1\u20130 victory that secured qualification for the [[UEFA Intertoto Cup|Intertoto Cup]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/4957460.stm |title=Newcastle 1\u20130 Chelsea |date=7 May 2006 |access-date=21 March 2009 |publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 August 2006, Bramble scored another vital goal for Newcastle in the [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]] second qualifying round with a header against Latvian side [[FK Ventspils]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/4775565.stm |title=FK Ventspils 0\u20131 Newcastle |date=10 August 2006 |access-date=7 July 2013 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\nIn December, Bramble was admitted into hospital after his injured calf swelled to double its normal size.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/n/newcastle_united/6176387.stm |title=BBC SPORT &#124; Football &#124; My Club &#124; Newcastle United &#124; Bramble in hospital after scare |date=13 December 2006 |access-date=21 March 2009 |publisher=BBC News}}</ref> On 31 January 2007, Bramble returned to action against Aston Villa in the centre of defence alongside [[Steven Taylor (footballer)|Steven Taylor]].<ref name=\"Soccerbase0607\" />\n\n===Wigan Athletic===\nBramble signed for [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]] on a free transfer, agreeing to a three-year-deal on 4 June 2007.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/wigan_athletic/6720701.stm |title=Wigan sign Bramble and Sibierski |date=4 June 2007 |work=BBC News}}</ref> On 2 January 2008, he scored a goal at Anfield in a 1\u20131 draw against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] \u2013 a 20-yard strike handing Wigan a late equaliser.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Fletcher |first=Paul |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/7163897.stm |title=BBC SPORT &#124; Football &#124; Premier League &#124; Liverpool 1\u20131 Wigan |date=2 January 2008 |access-date=16 July 2009 |publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nBramble scored an equaliser against Newcastle United at St. James' Park, the match finishing in a 2\u20132 draw on 15 November 2008.<ref name=\"Soccerbase0809\" /> His performances throughout the 2008\u201309 season picked him up four awards at the club's awards night, including 'Player of the Year' and 'Player's Player of the Year' for Wigan.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.wigantoday.net/sport/wigan-athletic/bramble-wins-four-awards-1-199173 |title=Bramble wins four awards |publisher=www.wigantoday.net |access-date=7 July 2013}}</ref> On 14 July 2009, he extended his contract with Wigan until 2012.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/jul/14/titus-bramble-emmerson-boyce-contract-extensions |title=Titus Bramble and Emmerson Boyce extend Wigan contracts to 2012 |date=14 July 2009 |work=The Guardian |access-date=7 July 2013 |location=London}}</ref>\n\n===Sunderland===\nOn 23 July 2010, Bramble joined [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] for \u00a31&nbsp;million. He signed a three-year contract at the [[Stadium of Light]], signed by his former manager at Wigan, Steve Bruce.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Stewart |first=Rob |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/sunderland/7901512/Titus-Bramble-to-be-reunited-with-Steve-Bruce-at-Sunderland.html |title=Titus Bramble to be reunited with Steve Bruce at Sunderland |date=21 July 2010 |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=London}}</ref> He scored his first and only Sunderland goal in a 4\u20130 win against [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] on 18 September 2011.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/14869926 |title=Sunderland 4\u20130 Stoke |publisher=BBC Sport |access-date=7 July 2013}}</ref> Bramble was one of seven players released by Sunderland at the end of the [[2012\u20132013 Premier League|2012\u201313 Premier League]] season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.premierleague.com/en-gb/news/news/2013-14/jun/summer-transfers-2013-ins-and-outs.html |title=Summer transfer window: Ins and Outs |publisher=Premier League |access-date=7 June 2013}}</ref> He played 51 games for Sunderland.<ref name=\"sb\">{{Soccerbase}}</ref>\n\nAfter being released by Sunderland he trained with [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] playing in their 6\u20132 pre-season defeat of [[Cork City F.C.|Cork City]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Bretland |first=Elliott |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2357978/Cork-City-2-West-Ham-6-Bramble-starts-Hammers-kick-pre-season-style.html |title=Bramble starts as Hammers kick off pre-season in style with win over Cork |date=8 July 2013 |access-date=24 July 2013 |publisher=Daily Mail |location=London}}</ref> He returned to Ipswich in the pre-season to train, making his playing return in a game against [[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]] but was not offered a contract.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ipswichstar.co.uk/sport/ipswich_town_sign_christophe_berra_on_a_two_year_deal_ending_their_interest_in_titus_bramble_1_2288627 |title=Ipswich Town sign Christophe Berra on a two-year deal, ending their interest in Titus Bramble |date=20 July 2013 |publisher=Ipswich Star |access-date=24 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Stowmarket Town===\nIn August 2017, having been without a club for four years, Bramble joined [[Stowmarket Town F.C.|Stowmarket Town]], of the [[Eastern Counties Football League]], as a [[player-coach]].<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\" />\n\n==Coaching career==\nBramble was appointed Under-11 coach at Ipswich Town. In November 2014, he said it was a \"disgrace\" to apply the \"[[Rooney Rule]]\" to English football for compulsory ethnic minority management candidate consideration.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/30017857 |title=Kieron Dyer & Titus Bramble do not want 'Rooney Rule' |date=12 November 2014 |access-date=12 November 2014 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nOne of his brothers, [[Tesfaye Bramble]], is a footballer and has represented [[Montserrat national football team|Montserrat]] at international level.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.gazette-news.co.uk/news/5431085.soccer-international-call-for-blues-striker/ |title=Soccer: International call for Blues striker |website=Gazette |language=en |access-date=20 February 2020}}</ref> The two brothers were arrested on suspicion of rape in September 2010<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-wear-11387989 |title=Sunderland's Titus Bramble arrested over rape claim |date=22 September 2010 |publisher=BBC News}}</ref> with Tesfaye being convicted of the offence,<ref name=\"Brother of footballer Titus Bramble guilty of rape\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-13805612 |title=Brother of footballer Titus Bramble guilty of rape |date=17 June 2011 |access-date=17 June 2011 |publisher=BBC}}</ref> and Titus later being released without charge. On 28 September 2011, Bramble was temporarily suspended by Sunderland,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/news-and-comment/sunderland-defender-titus-bramble-suspended-following-arrest-2362977.html |title=Sunderland defender Titus Bramble suspended following arrest |date=29 September 2011 |website=The Independent |language=en |access-date=20 February 2020}}</ref> after having been arrested on allegations of sexual assault and possession of a [[List of controlled drugs in the United Kingdom|Class A drug]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/28092011/58/premier-league-sunderland-bramble-arrested.html |title=Premier League \u2013 Sunderland's Bramble arrested |publisher=Yahoo Sport}}</ref> He was cleared of these charges on 31 May 2012.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Hartley-Parkinson |first=Richard |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2152712/BREAKING-NEWS-Titus-Bramble-cleared-sexually-assaulting-women.html?ito=feeds-newsxml |title=Titus Bramble cleared of sexually assaulting women |date=31 May 2012 |work=Daily Mail |access-date=31 May 2012 |last2=Allen |first2=Emily |location=London}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|FA Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|League Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other{{ref label|Other|A|}}\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|[[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]]\n|[